1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 ({The alternative move order} 4. Nf3 dxc4 5.
Qa4+ {[#] usually does not make much difference compared to 4.Bg2 and the game
transposes into the main line. There are still some differences that we have
to cover, though. I will make a note in places where transpositions into 4.Bg2
lines are possible.} {Now, as my goal with this opening repertoire is to give
you as much latitude as possible, I will look at both} Nbd7 ({and} 5... Bd7 6.
Qxc4 {Here, Black can continue in the classical way:} c5 ({or with a fairly
new idea} 6... b5 $5 {[#]} 7. Qc2 ({In case of} 7. Qd3 {black can play} c5 {
at once.}) 7... Na6 $5 {This is not a typical square for the knight in the
Catalan. Here, though, it works just fine.} 8. Bg2 (8. a3 {is superfluous as
black's idea with ...Na6 was not to continue ...Nb4, but rather to complete
queenside development and support ...c7-c5 break. Black easily obtained equal
chances in the following game:} c5 9. Bg2 Rc8 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 b4 12. axb4
Nxb4 13. Qd1 Bc6 14. O-O O-O $11 {0-1 (63) Gyokbulut,J (2098)-Batsiashvili,N 
(2435) Kocaeli 2014, and as it often happens in this type of position, a
stronger player eventually outplayed the weaker one.}) 8... c5 9. O-O Rc8 10.
Qd1 Bc6 {[#] Black completed his queenside development and achieved good
counterplay in the center, as can be seen from two GM games below:} 11. a4 (11.
Bg5 Be7 12. dxc5 O-O 13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. Nbd2 h6 15. Be3 Ng4 $15 {0-1 (38)
Antic,D (2442)-Aczel,G (2553) Palic SRB 2017}) 11... b4 12. Qd3 {1-0 (65)
Grachev,B (2673)-Oparin,G (2562) Moscow 2015} Nb8 13. Bg5 {[#] Black has a
choice between the simple} Be7 ({and more complex} 13... c4 $5 14. Qc2 Be7 15.
Nbd2 b3 $132) 14. Nbd2 Nbd7 15. Rfc1 O-O $11) 7. dxc5 (7. Bg2 {- Chapter 2})
7... Bc6 8. Nc3 (8. Be3 Nbd7 9. Bg2 {-4.Bg2 dxc4 5.Qa4+ Bd7 6.Qxc4 c5!} (9. Nc3
{-8.Nc3})) 8... Nbd7 9. Be3 {[#] The only move that makes sense for White. He
should make it more difficult for Black to return the pawn.} Rc8 10. Bg2 ({
Similar to 10.Bg2 is} 10. Rd1 Bxc5 $1 11. Bxc5 Bxf3 12. exf3 Rxc5 13. Qa4 a6
14. Be2 O-O 15. O-O Qc7 $11 {0-1 (52) Efimov,I (2480)-Renet,O (2494) France
2001}) ({An interesting possibility to imbalance the pawn structure is} 10. b4
$5 b6 11. Bg2 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfd1 bxc5 14. b5 Ba8 15. a4 Nd5 $13) 10...
Bxc5 $1 11. Bxc5 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Rxc5 {[#] White is optically better with his
Catalan bishop, but Black is extremely solid.} 13. Qb3 b6 14. O-O O-O 15. Rfd1
Qb8 16. Ne4 Rc7 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (67) Topalov,V (2804)-Anand,V 
(2803) Leon 2006}) ({Another major possibility for Black is} 5... c6 $5 {
but I decided to focus on variations where Black pushes the pawn to c5 as soon
as possible.}) 6. Qxc4 a6 {[#] Black prepares the extended fianchetto of his
light-squared bishop. At this point, the most sensible thing for White to do
is transpose into the main line with} 7. Bg2 {-4.Bg2} ({However, let us take a
look at a few alternatives met in practice. Firstly,} 7. a4 {does not stop
Black from completing his plan} b5 $1 {[#]} 8. Qc6 (8. axb5 $4 axb5 9. Qxb5
Rxa1 $18) 8... Rb8 9. axb5 Bb7 10. Qc2 axb5 11. Bg2 c5 12. O-O Qb6 13. Be3 Rc8
14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (32) Lehner,O (2260)-Casagrande,H 
(2340) Aschach 1995}) ({Developing queen's bishop at this point is
inconsistent:} 7. Bf4 c5 8. Bg2 b5 9. Qd3 c4 10. Qc2 Bb7 $15 {[#] Black
controls the e4-square and his queenside majority is much more potent than
White's pawn center.} 11. Nbd2 Nd5 12. a3 Be7 13. Ne4 O-O 14. Nc3 Nxf4 15. gxf4
Nf6 $15 {0-1 (41) Gagare,S (1989)-Vidit,S (2643) Pune IND 2015}) ({A similar
scenario was seen in} 7. Bg5 c5 8. Bg2 b5 9. Qd3 Bb7 10. O-O h6 11. Bxf6 Nxf6
12. Rd1 c4 13. Qc2 Be7 $15 {0-1 (47) Franco Alonso,A (2479)-Riazantsev,A (2712)
Eilat 2012})) 4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 {The main and most flexible continuation.}
({The alternative is} 5... Bd7 6. Qxc4 {with a nice tactical touch after} c5 $1
{[#] A really cool sacrifice that might take your opponent by surprise.} ({
Traditionally, the most common move has been} 6... Bc6 {when the games usually
continue} 7. Nf3 Bd5 8. Qd3 Be4 9. Qd1 c5 10. Nc3 Bc6 11. O-O Nbd7 {This does
not look like much for White, but let us not forget that he is already fully
