7. Qxc4 ({White can also postpone ...b7-b5 by one move with:} 7. Nc3 Rb8 8.
Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3 ({White queen will be a bit misplaced in case of} 9. Qb3 Bb7 10.
O-O c5 11. Be3 (11. Bf4 Rc8 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $11) 11... Be7 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Qd1
O-O 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $11 {1-0 (62) Petrosian,T-Panno,O Los Angeles,CA 1963}) 9...
Bb7 10. Bf4 (10. O-O {usually just transposes into 10.Bf4 after} c5 11. dxc5
Bxc5 12. Bf4 Rc8 {-10.Bf4}) 10... Rc8 11. O-O c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 {[#] This is
the "tabiya" of this particular opening variation. It was a favorite position
of excellent endgame player Ulf Andersson because he preferred non-risk
positions with a minimal positional pressure. There are some modern players
who follow in his footsteps, although to my taste this position is a bit too
dry for White. There is a lot of opening theory here, so I will just present
the main directions in which the game can develop, supported by some practical
examples:} 13. Rad1 (13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Nxe5 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. Bxe5 Ke7 17.
Rfd1 Ng4 18. Bxg7 Nxf2 19. Bxh8 Nxd1 20. Rxd1 Rxh8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Grachev,B
(2650)-Khismatullin,D (2639) Moscow 2017}) (13. Ng5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 O-O $11 15.
a4 $6 h6 16. Nf3 b4 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Qb6 19. Rac1 Nf6 20. Qb1 g5 21. Be5
Nd7 $15 {1/2-1/2 (31) Kurajica,B (2551)-Ragger,M (2670) Istanbul 2012}) (13. a3
O-O 14. Rad1 Qb6 15. e4 {[#] is an unconventional attempt by young Iranian GM
to make things more dynamic:} Rfd8 16. Qe2 h6 17. e5 Nd5 (17... Ng4 $5 $13) 18.
Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 $1 exd5 20. b4 Be7 21. Bh3 $44 Nf8 (21... Qg6 $13) 22. Bxc8
Rxc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (53) Maghsoodloo,P (2575)-Korobov,A (2691) Moscow 2017})
13... O-O 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Be7 17. Qf3 (17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rd1 Rxd1 20. Nxd1 Nd5 21. Nc3 Nxc3 22. Bxc3 $11 {1/2 (33)
Kryakvin,D (2586)-Khismatullin,D (2652) Taganrog RUS 2013}) 17... Qb6 18. Rd2
Rfd8 19. Rfd1 Rxd2 20. Rxd2 Qc6 21. Qxc6 Rxc6 22. h3 h5 23. f4 Kf8 24. Kf3 {
[#] This is a typical position for Andersson's opus. I would say the
probability of a draw is 90% and White winning 10% in a game between two
players of similar strength. For some people, as long as there is no risk
involved, this is enough...} Ne8 25. Rd7 f6 26. Bb8 Rb6 27. Ba7 Rd6 28. Rxd6
Nxd6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Andersson,U (2575)-Sunye Neto,J (2510) Rio de Janeiro
1985}) 7... b5 8. Qc6 {[#] The only principled continuation. White wins a
tempo and blocks the c7-pawn.} ({Obviously, then,} 8. Qc2 $6 {or any other
queen retreat gives black a free hand to complete his development smoothly:}
Bb7 9. O-O c5 {[#] This position has been seen very often in practice. It
looks reasonable for White at first, but in reality, he faces problems with
optimal placement of his dark-squared bishop and his queen. It might be too
early to say that Black objectively has an advantage, but the position is
definitely easier to play for him and the score in the database confirms this
evaluation. Here are some examples:} 10. a4 (10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Rc8 12. a3
O-O 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. e3 Qb6 16. Qe2 Rfd8 $15 {0-1 (34) Sharevich,A
(2305)-Vasilevich,I (2389) Istanbul 2005}) (10. Bg5 Rc8 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Nbd2
cxd4 13. Qd3 Bc5 14. Nb3 O-O 15. Nfxd4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qd5+ 17. Nf3 Qxd3 18. exd3
Bb6 $15 {0-1 (65) Zapata Ferrada,M (2378)-Vescovi,G (2631) Mar del Plata 2009})
(10. Nbd2 Rc8 11. Qd3 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 13. Qh4 Be7 14. Qd4 O-O (14... e5 $1
$36 15. Nxe5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bc5 17. Qf4 Bd6 18. Nxf7 Bxf4 19. Nxd8 Bxd2 $19) 15.
Nb3 Nd5 16. Qd1 Qc7 17. Bd2 Qb8 $15 {0-1 (38) Abdel Razik,K (2444)-Adly,A 
(2594) Tunis TUN 2013}) 10... b4 11. Nbd2 Rc8 $15 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Qd1 Be7 14.
b3 Nd5 $17 {0-1 (30) Garcia Ares,F (2240)-Korneev,O (2580) Zaragoza 1999}) 8...
Rb8 9. Bf4 {The logical-follow up, c7-pawn is under pressure.} Bb7 $1 {[#] The
most active continuation, fully in the spirit of modern chess. Black
sacrifices a pawn to complete his development and obtain activity.} ({The
"old" continuation is} 9... Nd5 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nc3 {etc.}) 10.
Qxc7 Bb4+ 11. Nbd2 Qxc7 12. Bxc7 Rc8 13. Bf4 Rc2 $36 {[#] All of this was
pretty much forced. With such active pieces, Black's compensation is obvious,
but he needs to continue energetically in order to make something out of it.
White is up a pawn, after all. Here White has three possibilities, the
strongest one being:} 14. Rb1 $1 {The critical move, keeping material and
asking Black to prove his compensation.} (14. O-O {is too cooperative. Black
returns the pawn in the best possible way with} Nd5 $1 15. Nb3 (15. Rfd1 Rxb2
16. a3 Ba5 17. Bd6 Nc3 18. Re1 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Nxe2+ 20. Kf1 Bxe1 $19 {0-1 (30)
Ulziibayar,B (2219)-Batchuluun,T (2521) Govi Altai 2014}) 15... Rxb2 {[#] The
material is equal, but Black's pressure remains:} 16. Bd2 Nc3 17. Bxc3 Bxc3 18.
Rfc1 b4 $15 {1/2 (29) Oll,L (2645)-Morozevich,A (2590) Groningen 1997}) (14. a3
Bxd2+ 15. Bxd2 Rxb2 {[#] also allows Black to recoup the pawn, but at least
White gets some dark-square control in return. While Black was doing well in
the games below, improvements could be made along the way:} 16. Bc3 (16. Kd1
O-O 17. Kc1 Rb3 18. Kc2 Bd5 19. Rhc1 Nb6 20. Bb4 Rc8+ 21. Kd1 {1-0 (42)
Oganian,M (2452)-Khomeriki,N (2317) Moscow 2017} Rxc1+ $1 22. Kxc1 (22. Rxc1
Rb2 $15) 22... Na4 $15) 16... Rc2 17. Bb4 $13 Nb6 18. e3 $6 {0-1 (52) Drygalov,
S (2372)-Riazantsev, A (2646)/Chelyabinsk RUS 2016/The Week in Chess 1125} Nc4
$1 19. O-O a5 20. Ne1 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rb2 22. Nd3 Nxe3+ $17) 14... Bxd2+ $1 {
[#] A somewhat counter-intuitive exchange, but the idea is to make it more
difficult for White to castle. This move has not been met in tournament
practice, but it has been the main choice of correspondence players.} ({
Natural, but not so strong is} 14... O-O 15. O-O Bxf3 $2 {Black went down very
quickly with this materialistic operation.} ({He would still keep some
compensation with} 15... Nd5 {instead.} 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 17. Nb3 Nxf4 18. gxf4 Bd5
19. Rxc2 Rxc2 20. e3 $14) 16. Nxf3 $16 Rxe2 $2 17. a3 Be7 18. Rfc1 $18 {
1-0 (31) Kasimdzhanov,R (2690)-Dizdarevic,E (2491) Eilat 2012}) 15. Bxd2 O-O {
Castling is impossible now, so White has to resort to less natural ways to
complete his development and, preferably, kick out the annoying rook from c2.}
16. Nh4 ({The alternative} 16. Kd1 {would allow} Be4 $1 {with some dangerous
tactical ideas, such as} 17. Nh4 Rfc8 18. Bc3 R2xc3 $1 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. bxc3
Nxc3+ $15) 16... Be4 ({I also investigated} 16... Ne4 $5 $146 {[#] which has
never been played, but looks very interesting. After} 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. f3 Bd5
19. Kd1 Rfc8 20. Bc3 {it seems like black is in trouble, but in fact, the
exchange sacrifice} R8xc3 $1 21. bxc3 Rxa2 {promises him good compensation due
to much better piece coordination. Here are some possible lines:} 22. Ng2 (22.
Rf1 Nb6 23. Rf2 Nc4 24. Ng2 Nd2 25. Rb4 Nxf3 $1 $44) 22... Bb3+ $1 23. Ke1 Bc4
24. Nf4 Nb6 $44) 17. Bf4 Bd5 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 19. Bd2 {[#]} f5 $5 $146 {I think
that preventing White's e2-e4 is more to the point} ({than} 19... N7b6 20. Kd1
Rfc8 21. e4 Nf6 22. f3 Na4 23. b3 Nb6 24. Ra1 Rb2 25. Rg1 Rcc2 26. Rg2 Rxa2 27.
Rxa2 Rxa2 28. Bc3 Rxg2 29. Nxg2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (38) Hildebrand,G (2375)-Popov,V 
(2129) ICCF email 2013}) 20. Kd1 Rfc8 $44 {and Black has a fairly typical
compensation for the pawn. For example:} 21. Ng2 (21. Rc1 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 N7b6
$44) 21... e5 $1 22. Ne1 R2c4 23. dxe5 Nxe5 $44 *

