1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 c5 6. Qa4+ {This check makes a
bit less sense now that Black has already played ...c7-c5.} (6. Na3 {[#] is an
even more rare alternative, but it usually just transposes into:} Nc6 7. Nxc4
cxd4 8. O-O {-Chapter 3}) 6... Bd7 7. Qxc4 Bc6 {[#]} 8. O-O (8. dxc5 Nbd7 {
is a position that we also briefly looked at in Chapter 1. Here are some
additional possibilities for White:} 9. Be3 (9. b4 a5 10. b5 Bd5 $132) (9. O-O
Bxc5 10. Nc3 Rc8 $11 11. Qh4 $6 O-O 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Rac1 Qb6 $15 {
1/2-1/2 (75) Adianto,U (2548)-Saric,A (2565) Biel 2013}) 9... Bd5 {[#]} 10. Qc2
(10. Qb4 a5 11. Qf4 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Nxc5 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qd4 Qb6
16. O-O {1/2-1/2 (16) Sosonko,G (2535)-Karpov,A (2715) Wijk aan Zee 1988} Rac8
17. Rac1 Rfd8 $11) (10. Qa4 Bc6 11. Qc4 Bd5 12. Qa4 Bc6 13. Qc4 {1/2-1/2 (13)
Rasmussen,A (2502)-Sengupta,D (2575) Hastings ENG 2017}) 10... Be4 11. Qc1 Bxc5
12. Bxc5 Rc8 13. b4 b6 14. Nc3 bxc5 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Qc4 {1/2-1/2 (28) Zhou,J
(2566)-Adams,M (2729) Khanty-Mansiysk 2007} Nd6 (16... Ndf6 $11) 17. Qf4 Qf6
$11) 8... Nbd7 9. Bg5 {[#] White often solves the issue of this (sometimes
problematic) bishop in the Catalan like this: he swaps it for Nf6 and then
removes his knight from f3 in order to swap off the light-squared bishops as
well. In some positions this strategy works well for White, but this is not
one of these positions.} ({The most common move here is} 9. Nc3 {but I fail to
see why Black would refrain from the active} b5 $1 {[#]} (9... Rc8 {as seen in
Radjabov,T (2745)-Anand,V (2783) Stavanger 2013, is the solid main line.}) 10.
Qd3 ({The tactical point is that} 10. Nxb5 $2 {does not work due to} Nb6 11.
Qc2 Bxb5 12. dxc5 Rc8) 10... c4 {[#] and we get a dynamic pawn structure that
will be explored more in Chapter 5. Here, it looks like a very good version
for Black since we can expand with a tempo on the next move and take control
of the e4 square:} 11. Qc2 (11. Qd1 {looks a bit inferior} b4 12. Nb1 Rc8 13.
Nbd2 Nb6 14. e3 c3 15. bxc3 bxc3 16. Nb3 Bb5 $15 {1-0 (36) Papaioannou,I (2405)
-Mastrovasilis,A (2210) Ikaros 1995}) 11... b4 12. Nb1 Rc8 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Nbd2
Nb6 $15 {I would rather have black pieces.}) ({A rare possibility is} 9. Rd1
Rc8 10. Be3 {[#] when Black again has an option to play for equality with} cxd4
({or for more with} 10... b5 $5 11. Qd3 c4 $132) 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qd3 Qb6 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (22) Lutsko,I (2487)-Teterev,V (2507) Minsk 2006}) (9. dxc5 Bxc5 {
-8.dxc5}) 9... Rc8 10. Bxf6 {White have scored well with this move.} (10. Nbd2
cxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. Rfc1 Ke7 $11 {[#] 1/2-1/2 
(32) Litvinov,V (2365)-Shereshevski,M Minsk (Belarus) 1985}) 10... Qxf6 $5 $146
{This move has been recommended by GM Ftacnik. Black queen usually feels less
comfortable on this square than one of the minor pieces. However, it is
difficult to see how White can create problems for his opponent. Black seems
to be doing just fine.} (10... gxf6 $5 {was a choice of GM Pinter. After} 11.
Nc3 b5 $132 12. Qd3 c4 13. Qc2 b4 14. Ne4 Nb6 $13 {[#] Inkiov,V (2485)-Pinter,
J (2575)/Zagreb 1987, a complicated middlegame was reached, where Black
definitely had his chances.}) ({The least successful was Korchnoi's choice
against Kasparov:} 10... Nxf6 11. dxc5 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Bxc5 13. Qb5+ Qd7 14. Nc3
Qxb5 15. Nxb5 Ke7 16. b4 Bxb4 17. Nxa7 Rc7 18. Rfc1 $36 {Kasparov,G (2690)
-Kortschnoj,V (2610)/London 1983}) 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Qd3 O-O $11 {[#] and
Black's excellent dark-square control gives him at least equal chances.} *

