1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Na3 {[#] This
is the least common of White's possibilities. The idea is to complete
queenside development as soon as possible at the cost of the central pawn.
However, it will be almost impossible for Black to hold on to that pawn while
trying to complete his own development. Objectively, these two factors should
balance each other out and the ensuing middlegame should be approximately
equal.} cxd4 8. Nxc4 Bc5 {There is no need to be too creative - the bishop
stands well on this square, supporting the d4-pawn.} 9. a3 {This move provokes
weakening of b5 and b6 squares, which makes sense from White's perspective.} (
{Several other alternatives have been tried, most notably:} 9. b3 {[#] The
bishop is usually developed to f4 in this variation; here we have a different
approach.} Qe7 10. Nfe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 {White intends to put the pressure along
the h1-a8 diagonal and return the pawn on d4 at some point. Both continuations
below give black a good game:} Nd7 (11... O-O 12. Bb2 Rd8 13. Rc1 {1/2-1/2 (67)
Melkumyan,H (2642)-Grachev,B (2654) Tbilisi GEO 2017} Bb6 14. Qd2 Nd7 15. Nc4
e5 {[#]} 16. Ba3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Nxc5 $132) 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Rc1 Rd8 14. Nd3 Bb6
15. Bc7 Re8 $11 16. Qc2 e5 17. Rfd1 Nf8 18. a4 Bg4 19. Bxb6 axb6 $15 {1/2-1/2 
(31) Carlsen,M (2837)-Anand,V (2782) London ENG 2017}) (9. Nfe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5
O-O 11. Bf4 Nd5 12. Rc1 {½-½ (53) Beliavsky,A (2619)-Naiditsch,A (2678)
Dresden 2008} Nxf4 13. gxf4 Bb6 $15) (9. Qc2 O-O (9... Qe7 $5 {[#] to protect
the c5-bishop, deserves attention as well.}) 10. Nce5 {was an interesting
concrete idea in Nakamura, H (2775)-Kaidanov, G (2594) Saint Louis 2012. White
is trying to obtain the bishop pair in return for the pawn. Black gets a good
game with} Nxe5 11. Qxc5 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Qb6 $1 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Bf4 Nd5 15.
Be5 d3 $1 $11) 9... a5 10. b3 ({White's opening strategy was not too
successful in the following two games (although White won both!):} 10. Bf4 O-O
11. Rc1 Nd5 {[#] This move shows why stronger players prefer to develop their
bishop on b2, rather than f4, in this line. Black will get a better pawn
structure after the exchange on f4.} 12. Nce5 Nxf4 13. Rxc5 Nxe5 14. gxf4 Nxf3+
15. Bxf3 {1-0 (32) Abasov,N (2516)-Rzayev,B (2432) Baku 2014} Qd6 $15) (10. Bd2
O-O 11. Rc1 Be7 12. Bf4 Nd5 13. Nce5 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Nxe5 15. fxe5 d3 16. Qxd3
Qxd3 17. exd3 {1-0 (43) Wen,Y (2573)-Ma,Z (2468) China 2015} Rb8 $15) 10... O-O
11. Bb2 $44 {[#] ½-½ (42) Dubov,D (2666)-Fridman,D (2640) Tbilisi GEO 2017.
There is no doubt that White has a compensation for the pawn. Among several
good possibilities, I would suggest the following way of completing Black's
development:} Rb8 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb7b6] preparing b7-b6. The rook will also be
useful on the b-file should an exchange of knights happen on c6.} 12. Nfe5 Bd7
13. Rc1 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qe7 15. a4 Rfc8 {[#] Black has completed his development
smoothly. White gets his pawn back,} 16. Bxd4 {but that is about all there is
to it. The position after} Be8 $11 {looks absolutely equal.} *

