1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5 {[#] An
aggressive continuation - White opens the diagonal for his Catalan bishop
without hesitation. Capturing the knight on e5 or pawn on d4 are not
attractive to Black for different reasons, but the solid developing move} Bd7
{works well. Now, the main continuation} 8. Na3 {reminds us of Chapter 3,
where White played the same way with his queen's knight.} ({Let us see what
happens if White takes the c4-pawn with the other knight:} 8. Nxc4 cxd4 9. Bf4
{[#] This was White's idea - d6-square is vulnerable. Here,} Be7 $1 {has
replaced} ({the old line} 9... Nd5 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Nde7 12. Nd2 $44) {
as the main continuation for White. The point is that after} 10. Nd6+ (10. Qb3
{is inconsistent} O-O 11. Qxb7 Rc8 $11) 10... Kf8 {Black keeps his bishop pair.
White wins a less valuable pawn (b7 instead of d4):} 11. Nxb7 Qb6 12. Nd6 (12.
Qb3 $2 e5 13. Bd2 Rb8 $17) 12... Qc5 $1 {[#] and we get a critical position.
Now, the most popular way to deal with the threat to d6-knight is:} 13. Qb3 $5
({White would ideally like to make the developing} 13. Nd2 {work, but Black has
} e5 $1 (13... Bxd6 14. Rc1 $36) 14. N6e4 (14. Rc1 $5 Qxd6 15. Nc4 Qb4 16. Nxe5
Nxe5 17. Bxa8 Ng6 $13) 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qb6 {[#] and he takes the
initiative in the center.} 16. Bd2 $6 f5 17. Ng5 h6 $36 {Weise,D-Krieger,H/
Menden 1974/EXT 2001 (1/2, 52).}) ({An interesting attempt to improve on this
idea is a spirited pawn sacrifice} 13. b4 $5 {[#]} Qxb4 14. a3 Qc5 15. Nd2 e5 (
15... Bxd6 $2 16. Nb3 $18) 16. N2e4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Qb6 18. Rb1 {White opened a
file on the queenside, hoping to take advantage of Black's uncastled king.} Qc7
19. Bd2 f5 20. Ng5 ({The spectacular} 20. f4 $6 {seems to be unsound:} fxe4 21.
fxe5+ Ke8 $1 22. Bf4 Be6 23. Bxe4 Rc8 24. Qa4 Qd7 $17 {Romanov,E (2554)-Meier,
G (2556)/Neustadt 2008/CBM 126 Extra (0-1, 43)}) 20... h6 21. Nf3 Kf7 {Black
is about to consolidate and White tried his last chance to open up the
position:} 22. e3 $1 {but after} e4 $1 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 24. exd4 Rab8 {[#] Black
was solid in Gelfand,B (2723)-Adams,M (2729)/Yerevan 2008/CBM 124 Extra (1/2,
42)}) (13. Ne4 {is the simplest solution, but Black faces no problems after}
Nxe4 14. Bxe4 g5 ({Probably, no worse is} 14... e5 $5 15. Bd2 f5 16. Bg2 Rb8
$13) 15. Bd2 (15. Bc1 f5 16. Bg2 Rc8 17. e3 Bf6 18. Nc3 Rd8 19. exd4 Nxd4 20.
Be3 Bc6 $132 {Loginov,V (2496)-Zacurdajev,M (2384)/St Petersburg 2007/CBM 118
ext (0-1, 59)}) 15... Rb8 16. Na3 Rxb2 17. Rc1 Qxa3 18. Bxc6 Qxa2 19. Bxg5 Bxg5
20. Qxd4 Bxc1 21. Qxh8+ Ke7 22. Bxd7 Kxd7 23. Rxc1 Rb1 $11 {1/2 (25) Loginov,V
(2516)-Yevseev,D (2580)/St Petersburg 2004/CBM 101}) 13... Bxd6 14. Rc1 {
White will win the knight on c6, in turn.} Qb4 15. Qxb4 (15. Bxc6 Rc8 16. Bxd7
Rxc1+ 17. Bxc1 Qe1+ 18. Kg2 Qxc1 $11) 15... Bxb4 16. Bxc6 Rc8 {[#] and after
this, more or less, forced sequence the position has simplified considerably.
White is hoping to make something of his queenside majority in the endgame.}
17. Bxd7 (17. Rc4 Rxc6 18. Rxb4 e5 $1 $146 19. Bxe5 Rc1+ 20. Kg2 Ke7 $132 {
[%cal Gd7f5]}) (17. a3 Be7 18. Bxd7 Rxc1+ 19. Bxc1 Nxd7 20. Nd2 f6 $11 {
[%cal Gf8f7,Ge6e5]}) 17... Rxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Nxd7 19. Bd2 {[#] This is still the
main line of White's idea. Black needs to show some precision now and Kramnik
does exactly that:} a5 $1 ({After} 19... Bc5 20. Na3 Ke7 21. b4 {Black should
still be okay, but why allow White to expand so easily?}) 20. a3 Bxd2 21. Nxd2
Ke7 22. Nb3 Rb8 $1 23. Nxa5 Rxb2 {[#] All of this is very concrete, but at the
same time not too difficult to remember. Black just plays the most active
moves.} 24. Nc6+ Kf6 25. a4 (25. Nxd4 e5 $11) 25... Rxe2 26. Nxd4 Rd2 27. Nb5
Rd5 28. Rb1 Rd2 {Threatening to put the rook behind the pawn.} 29. Ra1 Rd5 $11
{1/2-1/2 (31) Leko,P (2734)-Kramnik,V (2790) Dortmund 2010 CBM 138 [Marin,M]})
({Much less principled for White is to make the following exchanges:} 8. Nxc6
Bxc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 ({The endgame after} 10. dxc5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12.
Nd2 Rd8 13. Rf1 {[#]} c3 $1 14. bxc3 O-O $11 {is just equal.}) 10... cxd4 11.
Qxc6+ Nd7 12. Qxc4 Bc5 $11 {[#] Black defends the central pawn and completes
his development in one move.} 13. Nd2 (13. b4 Be7 14. Bb2 e5 15. a3 O-O 16. Nd2
Nb6 17. Qb5 Rc8 18. Rac1 Qd5 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (36) Siewert,W (2339)
-Calugaru,V (2301) LSS email 2008}) 13... O-O 14. Ne4 Bb6 15. Bg5 Ne5 16. Bxd8
Nxc4 17. Bxb6 axb6 18. b3 Na3 $11 {1/2-1/2 (37) Yegiazarian,A (2426)-Petrosyan,
M (2443) Yerevan 2015}) 8... cxd4 9. Naxc4 Be7 $5 {[#] This move should allow
Black to solve his opening problems.} (9... Bc5 {is a bit more common, though
the bishop is also more exposed on c5.}) 10. Qb3 {The main line.} ({The
alternative is} 10. Bf4 Rc8 11. Qb3 ({White's attempt to capitalize on the
bishop pair after} 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 {[#] should be
neutralized in more than one way. I would suggest} Rd8 $5 $146 14. Qd3 O-O 15.
Rfd1 Qa4 $5 16. Bxb7 Qa5 $1 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 $11) 11... Nd5 12. Qxb7 Nxe5 13. Nxe5
Rc7 14. Qb3 (14. Qa6 Nxf4 15. gxf4 O-O $11 16. Rfc1 Qc8 17. Qxc8 Rfxc8 18. Rxc7
Rxc7 19. Nxd7 {1/2-1/2 (19) Svidler,P (2750)-Bacrot,E (2714) France 2010})
14... Nxf4 15. gxf4 O-O {[#] White got his pawn back and his pieces are more
active, but black has some positional trumps (better structure and bishop pair)
, so the position is equal.} 16. Rfd1 (16. Rfc1 Qc8 $11) 16... Bc5 17. Rac1 Bb6
18. Nc4 Bc5 19. Ne5 Bb6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (20) Stefanova,A (2464)-Meier,G (2570)
Reykjavik 2008}) 10... Qc7 $1 {[#] This direct approach to solving Black's
problems has to be well-calculated. These days, we can rely on our silicon
friend to do that job for us without the risk of making an error.} 11. Bf4 ({
Less critical is} 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bf4 Qd8 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Ne5 (14. Qa4 O-O
15. Qxc6 Rc8 16. Qa4 Nd5 $15 {Marin,M: '1/2-1/2 (16) Shirov,A (2679)-Landa,K 
