1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 {[#]
These days this is the most popular continuation on the highest level. Just as
in the Queen's gambit accepted, White tries to put pressure on Black in a
fairly symmetrical queenless middlegame/endgame. Compared to that position (1.
d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 e6 5.Bxc4 a6 6.0-0 c5 7.dxc5), the improvement
for White is that his bishop is placed much more aggressively on h1-a8 diagonal.
However, Black also has a comparative advantage - he has not weakened his
queenside with a7-a6 move. The following variations will show that White's
initiative is real, but can be neutralized with precise play.} Qxd1 8. Rxd1
Bxc5 9. Nbd2 {is by far, the main variation} ({However, recently} 9. Nfd2 $5 {
[#] caught the attention of some strong players as well.} Na5 10. Na3 (10. Nc3 {
is another idea:} Bd7 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb4 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Bc6 $1
$11 {[#] and the Catalan bishop has been neutralized.}) 10... Bxa3 11. bxa3 {
[#] Such positions are not uncommon for the Catalan opening. White sacrifices
a pawn, hoping to utilize his bishop pair and semi-open d- and b-files. In a
practical game, this approach can be quite unpleasant for Black if he plays
inaccurately.} Nd5 {The most active continuation.} ({Recently, Anand opted for
} 11... O-O {instead.} 12. Ne4 (12. Bb2 {is also possible but should be fine
for Black after} Nd5 13. Rac1 b5 14. a4 a6 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Ne4 Rd8 17. Nd6 Rb8
$11) 12... Nxe4 (12... Nd5 {still transposes into 11...Nd5}) 13. Bxe4 e5 {
[#] This is Black's point. He limits the scope of White's dark-squared bishop
and opens up the diagonal for his own bishop.} 14. Bb2 Nc6 (14... Re8 $5 {
[%csl Ge5] might be a more accurate move order as it does not allow White to
capture the e5 pawn} 15. Bc3 Nc6 16. Rab1 Nd8 $1 17. f3 {-14...Nc6}) 15. f3 (
15. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 16. Bxe5 Bf5 17. Bc3 {should be quite drawish, of course,
though White is up a pawn on the kingside. 14...Re8 would circumvent this
option for White.} Rfe8 18. Rd2 Rad8 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. f3 f6 21. Kf2 h5 22. Rc1
Kf7 23. Ba5 Rd4 $11) 15... Re8 16. Rab1 f6 17. Bc3 Nd8 $1 {[#] An excellent
defensive move by Anand. The knight defends b7, so the bishop will be free the
move.} 18. a4 Rb8 19. a5 Be6 20. a4 a6 21. Rb6 Bf7 $1 22. Rd7 (22. h4 Bg6 $11)
22... Be6 23. Rc7 Rc8 24. Rxc8 (24. Rcxb7 $5 {was a very interesting
alternative to complicate matters - something I think Magnus Carlsen would
seriously consider.} f5 $1 (24... Nxb7 25. Bxb7 Rc7 26. Bxa6 $36) 25. Rxe6 Nxe6
26. Bxf5 g6 27. Bg4 $44) 24... Bxc8 25. Bd5+ Be6 26. Bxb7 Nxb7 27. Rxb7 Ra8 28.
Kf2 Bf7 29. Rc7 Be8 30. Rxc4 Bd7 $11 {[#] and Anand defended successfully in
Dominguez Perez, L (2739)-Anand, V (2768) Saint Louis USA 2018. Despite a very
good performance, this still felt like a laborious draw, so I would be
inclined to play the more active 11...Nd5, instead.}) 12. Ne4 O-O 13. Bd2 {[#]}
b6 {It makes sense to complete the development as soon as possible.} ({However,
I believe that the slower} 13... Nc6 $5 $146 {should work for Black as well.
After} 14. Rac1 ({or} 14. Nd6 c3 15. e4 cxd2 16. exd5 exd5 17. Rxd2 Be6 $11)
14... b6 {[#] Black will retreat his knight to e7, play Ba6 and achieve
comfortable equality:} 15. Nc3 (15. Rxc4 Nce7 16. Bb4 Ba6 $11) 15... Nce7 16.
Nxd5 Nxd5 17. e4 Nf6 18. Bb4 Re8 19. Rxc4 e5 $1 20. Rc7 Be6 $11) 14. Rac1 Rb8 (
{It seems inaccurate to play} 14... Ba6 {too early, as Carlsen demonstrated in
the following game:} 15. Bxa5 bxa5 16. Nc5 Bb5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 Rfd8 19.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Ne4 $1 f5 21. Nc3 Bc6 22. f3 $14 {[#] with a slow and
