[#] and Black's strong control over dark-squares promises equality.} 28. Bb4+
Be7 29. Bc3 (29. Be1 Bd6 30. a5 Na3 31. Bc6 $6 Nb8 $15) 29... Bf6 {1/2-1/2 (29)
Gagliardi,V (2190)-Rawlings,A (2367) ICCF email 2015}) 21... Rxe7 22. f4 {
This is probably more critical} ({than} 22. Rc1 g5 $1 23. Nd4 Kg7 24. Rc8 Rd7
25. e3 {[#] White displays some activity, but Black is extremely solid. My
first instinct is to fix the kingside with} g4 $5 $146 {and the engine agrees.
It is surprising that this natural move has never been played.} ({Instead,} 
25... Nd5 26. Bxd5 Rxd5 27. Rc7 g4 $1 28. Kg2 {1/2-1/2 (66) Lei,T (2455)-Zhang,
X (2364) Wuxi 2015} (28. Nxe6+ Kf6 29. Nd4 Nf3+ 30. Nxf3 (30. Kg2 Nxd4 31. exd4
Rxb5 32. Rxa7 Rb2 33. a3 h5 34. Rb7 Ke6 $11) 30... gxf3 31. h4 Rxb5 32. Rxa7
Ke6 33. Kh2 h5 $11) 28... Kf6 $1 29. Rxa7 {[#]} Nc4 $44) ({and} 25... Nd3 {
were met in practice. Black was slightly worse, but still solid enough in most
cases.} 26. Bc6 Re7 27. h3 Nc5 28. g4 h6 29. Kg2 Nfe4 30. Bxe4 Nxe4 31. Kf3
Nd2+ 32. Ke2 Ne4 33. a4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Emrich,E (2308)-Uecker,D (2305) GER
email 2016}) {The game could continue:} 26. Kf1 (26. Bc6 Re7 $11) 26... Nd3 27.
Bc6 Re7 28. Nb3 Nb4 29. a3 Nxc6 30. bxc6 Nd5 31. Nd4 Rc7 $11) 22... Nc4 23. Rc1
Nd6 {[#]} 24. Rd1 $5 {An enterprising pawn sacrifice.} ({A slower approach} 24.
a4 {gives White a small positional pressure in the endgame:} h6 25. Rc6 Rd7 26.
Nd4 g5 $11 {[#] though it is difficult to make any progress - Black is just
too solid.}) 24... Nxb5 25. Bc6 $1 Nc7 26. Rd8+ Nfe8 27. Nd4 $36 {Black needs
to thread carefully now.} Kf8 $1 28. Bf3 (28. Kf2 e5 $11) 28... Nd5 (28... e5
$6 29. Nc6) 29. e4 Nb4 30. a3 e5 $1 {[#] This leads to simplifications.} 31.
axb4 exd4 32. e5 (32. Rxd4 Rc7 33. Kf2 Ke7 $11) 32... a5 33. bxa5 bxa5 34. Bc6
d3 $1 $132 35. Kf2 d2 36. Kf3 d1=Q+ 37. Rxd1 Rc7 38. Be4 Rc3+ 39. Ke2 Nc7 40.
Rb1 g6 41. Rb7 Rc5 42. Kd3 h5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (48) Turgut,T (2617)-Glukhovtsev,S 
(2407) ICCF email 2015} *

