1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 Bd7 {6.Ne5 is the most natural
and popular move against the sharp 5...Bd7 variation, but that does not mean
that it is the only challenging option White has at his disposal. In this
Chapter, we will take a look at two more interesting ways that White can try
to pose problems to Black in the opening.} {Firstly, White can try to win back
the c-pawn with} 6. Nbd2 ({Secondly, he can continue in gambit style:} 6. O-O
Bc6 {[#]} 7. Qc2 {This looks like a critical try. White allows Black to defend
the c-pawn, so we get a sharp position early on - just as we wanted.} (7. a4 {
[#] is a common move. White makes sure that Black cannot support his c-pawn
with ...b7-b5, but I believe that Black, in turn, can use the drawback of
a2-a4 advance to his advantage:} Bb4 $5 $146 8. Qc2 a5 9. Qxc4 O-O {[#] This
position reminds me of the main line of 4...Be7 variation. Control over
b4-square is an important positional trump for Black.} 10. Bd2 (10. Bg5 h6 11.
Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Ne5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 c5 $11) (10. Nc3 Nbd7 $11) 10... Na6 $11) ({
Continuing in the Catalan gambit style:} 7. Nbd2 b5 8. Qc2 ({The central plan
with:} 8. a4 $6 a6 9. Qc2 Be7 10. e4 O-O 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8
Bxa8 $17 {proved to be ineffective in Gunina,V (2525)-Ju Wenjun (2579) Doha
QAT 2016}) 8... Be7 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 $44 {[#] also deserves attention.
White had compensation in the following game, but not more:} O-O 11. Bb2 (11.
Ba3 $5 $44) 11... Bb7 (11... a5 $5 12. Rfc1 Ra6) 12. Rfc1 Na6 13. Ne5 Bxg2 14.
Rxa6 Bb7 15. Nc6 Qd7 16. Raa1 (16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Ra5 $44) 16... Qxc6 17. Qxc6
Bxc6 18. Rxc6 Bb4 19. Nf3 a5 20. Rxc7 Nd5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (38) Zoler,D (2497)
-Gindi,S (2391) Herzliya ISR 2017}) (7. Bg5 Be7 8. Qc2 b5 {-7.Qc2}) 7... b5 8.
a4 (8. Nc3 $5 {[#] has been played only in Stopa,J (2544)-Viterbo Ferreira,J 
(2447) Porto 2015, but it deserves more credit. Instead of 8...b4 played in
that game, Black may wait for White to play e2-e4 before attacking the knight:}
Be7 9. e4 b4 {Now, the principled continuation is} 10. d5 bxc3 11. dxc6 {when}
Qd3 $1 {[#] keeps the position roughly level. For example:} 12. Qa4 O-O 13. Ne5
Qd6 14. Nxc4 Qxc6 15. Qxc6 Nxc6 16. bxc3 Rab8 $1 17. Bf4 Rb5 18. Bxc7 Rc5 $11)
(8. Bg5 Be7 9. a4 a6 10. Nc3 {was seen in Eljanov,P (2418)-Moiseenko,A (2419)
Kharkov 1999. Again, I would prefer a developing move over 10...b4:} Nbd7 11.
e4 O-O 12. Rfd1 {[#]} Bb7 $13) 8... a6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. e4 b4 11. d5 Bb7 {
[#] All of this was forced and principled from both sides. The position
becomes quite sharp now, with mutual chances:} 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Ng5 {1-0 (38)
Wendt,J (2304)-Berczes,C (2340) Budapest 2004} (13. Ne2 Bxe4 14. Qxc4 {0-1 (77)
Verstraeten,R (2312)-Geirnaert,S (2451) Schelle 2015} Bd5 15. Qc2 Be4 16. Qd1
e5 $13) 13... bxc3 $1 14. Nxe6 Qe7 15. Nxc7+ Kf7 16. Nxa8 Bxa8 17. Qxc3 Qe6 $13
) (6. Qc2 c5 {- Chapter 2}) {Here, I would prefer to hold onto the pawn with}
6... Bb5 $5 {[#]} ({Alternatives are} 6... Bb4) ({and} 6... Bc6) 7. Ne5 {
Only this move is critical.} (7. O-O {is too slow. Black gets better chances
after} Nc6 {[#] and since 8.e3 loses the exchange to 8...c3, White may not
have anything better than} 8. Nb1 Be7 9. Nc3 Ba6 10. Qa4 O-O $15 {when it is
difficult to speak of compensation for the pawn.} 11. Rd1 Nd5 12. a3 Nb6 13.
Qc2 Na5 14. e4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Nxc1 16. Rbxc1 Qe8 17. h4 Rd8 $15 {0-1 (39) Li
Chao2 (2721)-Zhang Zhong (2614) Ho Chi Minh City VIE 2015}) (7. a4 $6 {is even
worse:} Ba6 8. a5 Nc6 9. Qa4 Qd6 $1 (9... Qd5 10. O-O Qb5 11. Qxb5 Bxb5 12. Nb1
Bb4 $15 {1/2-1/2 (34) Khotenashvili,B (2476)-Harika,D (2504) Riyadh KSA 2017})
10. Ne5 Nd5 $17 11. Nexc4 Qb4 $19) 7... a5 $1 {[#] This move provides space
for the rook and gives Black some tactical benefits at the same time. White
has two ways to recover the pawn:} 8. Ndxc4 (8. Bxb7 Ra7 {The problem for
White is that his d-pawn is hanging now.} 9. Bf3 (9. a4 $6 Rxb7 10. axb5 Qxd4
11. Nexc4 Bb4 12. Nxa5 Rxb5 13. Nab3 Qd5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (16) Ringoir,T (2474)
-Naroditsky,D (2634) Helsingor 2016}) 9... Qxd4 10. Nexc4 a4 $1 {[#] It is
useful to push the pawn to a4 in order to take up more space on the queenside.
After some exchanges in the center, we reached an imbalanced position. Both
sides still need to complete their development. One possible continuation is}
11. Qc2 Be7 12. O-O Nd5 13. Rd1 Nc6 14. Na3 Ncb4 $13) 8... Bb4+ {[#] Since the
bishop is protected by the a-pawn, White cannot play 9.Bd2, so he is forced
to give up the right to castle:} 9. Kf1 c6 10. Bf3 (10. a4 Ba6 11. Bf3 Nbd7 12.
Kg2 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 O-O 14. e3 Qe7 $11 {also looks totally harmless. The bishop
is actually placed quite well on a6.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Kg2 {[#] White has taken
the longer way to bring his king to safety. The position resembles some
branches of the Slav defense, where Black is very solid. His bishop is on g6
or h7 there, whereas here it is on an unusual diagonal. But overall, I would
say that Black should be satisfied with opening results.} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 a4 $5
$146 {is a possible improvement over the GM game below.} (12... Nd7 13. Nd3 Be7
14. Qc2 O-O 15. Rd1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (35) Wei,Y (2748)-Ghosh,D (2556) Ashkhabad
2017}) 13. a3 Ba5 14. e3 O-O 15. Qc2 Nd7 16. Nc4 {[#]} Bc7 $11 *

