1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 {
[#] In this chapter, we will take a look at some rare alternatives to the main
move 8.0-0.} {The most common one is} 8. Qa4 (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[#] As we have
already seen in previous chapters, White must have a very good reason to swap
the Catalan bishop. In this instance, it is premature as he can not take
advantage of Black's tripled pawns without any developed pieces.} 9. O-O (9.
Qa4 Qd5 10. O-O Qb5 $11 {[#] is at least equal, but probably already
preferable for Black, as the games below suggest:} 11. Nc3 (11. Qc2 Rd8 12. Nc3
Qa5 13. Be3 Bd6 14. Qa4 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 Rb8 16. a3 Nd5 17. Rfc1 c3 $1 $15 18. b4
a5 $1 19. Nxc3 axb4 20. Nxd5 cxd5 21. axb4 Kd7 $17 {0-1 (71) Aranha Filho,A 
(2277)-Delgado Ramirez,N (2604) Cuiaba 2015}) 11... Qxa4 12. Nxa4 Rb8 13. Bd2
Bb4 14. Rfd1 Ne4 15. Bxb4 Rxb4 $15 {0-1 (34) Exler,V (2189)-Harika,D (2521)
Tromso 2014}) 9... c5 10. Be3 (10. dxc5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12. Nd2 O-O-O 13.
Rf1 c3 $1 14. bxc3 $11 {0-1 (30) Pogan,N (2232)-Bhakti,K (2363) Olomouc CZE
2016}) 10... Nd5 {[#] A standard reaction to Be3.} 11. Qa4+ Qd7 12. Qxd7+ (12.
Qxc4 Nxe3 13. fxe3 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. exd4 Rd8 16. e3 c5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (97)
Arvola,B (2385)-Prohaszka,P (2592) Fagernes 2017}) 12... Kxd7 13. dxc5 $11 {
in most of these lines, it is White who struggles to keep the balance.}) (8. e3
Qd7 {[#] can actually transpose into the main line that we cover in the
upcoming chapters, after 9.0-0. Let us see what happens if White postpones
castling and tries to win the c-pawn one move earlier:} 9. Qe2 e5 10. O-O exd4
11. exd4+ Be7 12. Qxc4 (12. d5 Nxd5 13. Rd1 Qe6 14. Qxc4 Ndb4 15. Qxe6 fxe6 16.
Nc3 {gives White some compensation, but there is no need for him to play this
way and try to achieve a draw at best.} Rd8 17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 18. a3 Nc2 19. Rb1
c6 20. Bf4 $44 {0-1 (42) Titan,M (2226)-Krysztofiak,M (2396) Graz AUT 2017})
12... O-O $11 {[#] In the position against the isolated queen's pawn, Black is
doing fine since he has several extra development tempi.} 13. Rd1 Rfd8 (13...
Rad8 14. Nc3 $6 (14. d5 $11) 14... Nxd4 15. Bxb7 Qg4 16. Bf4 Ne6 $15 {0-1 (40)
Polatel, A (2238)-Rozentalis, E (2513) Warsaw POL 2018}) 14. d5 {This advance
probably has to be made. It gives Black a lot of freedom on the dark-squares,
so it is not a surprise that White was happy with a quick draw in the
following game:} Ne5 15. Qe2 Bd6 16. Nc3 Re8 17. Bg5 Neg4 18. Qf3 Ne5 19. Qe2
Neg4 20. Qf3 {1/2 (20) Sosonko,G (2505)-Rodriguez Cespedes,A (2495)
Thessaloniki 1988}) 8... Qd7 9. Qxc4 ({Again, the exchange on c6 is inferior
to other options:} 9. Bxc6 $6 Qxc6 10. Qxc6+ bxc6 11. O-O {[#]} O-O-O $1 {
a convenient way to complete development and increase the pressure in the
center. Black is already for preference.} 12. Be3 (12. e3 c5 13. dxc5 Rd5 14.
c6 (14. Nc3 Rd3 15. c6 Bb4 16. Ne2 e5 $17 {0-1 (33) Yuan,Y (2212)-Ju Wenjun 
(2568) China CHN 2016}) 14... Rd6 15. b4 Rxc6 16. b5 Rc5 17. a4 c3 18. Ba3 Rc4
19. Bxf8 Rxf8 $17 {1/2-1/2 (42) Acosta,P (2409)-Villanueva,M (2451) Buenos
Aires ARG 2017}) 12... Nd5 $15 {0-1 (43) Jacutina,J (2081)-Zhang,Z (2318)
Bangkok 2017}) (9. e3 $6 Nb4 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. Na3 $2 (11. Kd2 c5 $1 $36)
11... Nd3+ 12. Ke2 Bxa3 13. bxa3 Rab8 14. Rd1 b5 $17 {0-1 (27) Zelesco,K (2318)
-Illingworth, M (2506) Cammeray AUS 2015}) 9... Nxd4 10. Bxb7 {White risks
being down a pawn for very little in return if he does not take it
immediately.} ({In case of} 10. O-O b5 $1 11. Qd3 Rd8 12. Be3 a6 {[#] it is
not simple for White to prove his compensation. In two games that continued
from this position, white players failed to do so:} 13. a4 Nf5 14. axb5 (14.
Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. Ba7 b4 $1 $15 16. e4 Nd6 17. Rc1 c5 18. Nd2 $2 Nc8 {0-1 (18)
Xiu,D (2557)-Mamedyarov,S (2743) China 2015}) 14... axb5 15. Rc1 (15. Qxd7+
Nxd7 16. Bf4 $44) 15... Qxd3 16. exd3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bd6 18. Bc6+ Ke7 19. Bxb5
h5 $17 {0-1 (41) Freeman,G (2156)-Tilicheev,V (2515) Dublin IRL 2018}) 10...
Rb8 11. Bg2 Bb4+ {[#]} 12. Nd2 ({In a similar position from the previous
chapter,} 12. Kf1 {was practically a forced answer to this check, but here it
is not. 12.Nd2 is better.} O-O 13. e3 Nf5 14. Bf3 e5 15. Kg2 e4 16. Be2 h5 $132
17. h3 Rfe8 18. a3 Bd6 $17 {0-1 (27) Gedajlovic,M (2302)-Shyam,S (2485) Sitges
ESP 2015}) 12... O-O 13. e3 (13. b3 $6 Rfd8 14. O-O Bc3 $1 $36 {[#] This
strong move gives Black an initiative that he did not let go off until the end
of the game:} 15. Rb1 Qb5 16. Qxb5 Rxb5 17. Re1 Rb6 18. e3 Nb5 19. Re2 Bb4 $1
20. Rb2 Na3 $1 21. Nf1 Bc3 $19 {0-1 (39) Pustovoitova,D (2304)-Moskalenko,A 
(2464) Sochi RUS 2016}) 13... Nf5 {White could maybe count on an advantage if
he had already castled. Here he still struggles to connect his forces into one
unit.} 14. Bc6 (14. Qe2 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qb5 $1 {stops White from castling.} 16.
Qe2 Qb4+ 17. Qd2 {[#] Black can force a draw with} Qb5 $11 {if he would like
to.}) 14... Qd6 15. a3 Ng4 $1 16. axb4 {This is neccessary.} ({White lost the
sense of danger and played} 16. Qc2 $2 Bc5 17. Be4 {[#] 1-0 (45) Wojtkiewicz,A
(2570)-Timoshenko,G (2592) Fredericksburg 1999} {and here Black had an
opportunity to punish him with} Bxe3 $1 18. fxe3 Nfxe3 $40 {with an
unstoppable attack. White is undeveloped and his king is exposed. For example:}
19. Qc3 Qb6 $1 20. h3 Ng2+ 21. Kd1 Nf2+ 22. Kc2 Ne3+ 23. Kb1 Nxh1 24. Bxh1 Nd1
25. Qc2 Qg1 $19) 16... Ne5 17. Ne4 Qxc6 18. Qxc6 Nxc6 19. Bd2 $11 *

