1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8.
e3 Qd7 9. O-O O-O-O {[#] I explained in the introduction that this risky
approach is not for those who are not willing to take a considerable amount of
risk. However, Black's overall score in this line is encouraging, which shows
that the position is also not so simple to handle with White. Whatever
motivation you have for playing this way against the Catalan (a surprise
weapon in blitz/rapid, your opponent is not a strong attacking player and
prefers positional play, you are in a must-win tournament situation, etc.),
you should start by carefully analyzing the variations I am about to show here.
} 10. Qa4 {is the most popular move and indeed the simplest approach to the
position. However, just as with other early queens moves that we have seen so
far, White is wasting some time and his development suffers a bit.} ({White
has two alternatives that address the issue of quick development. Firstly,
there is} 10. Nd2 {[#] planning to take on c4 with the knight, rather than
queen. However, this move also allows Black to strike in the center with} e5 $1
({A good example of what could happen if Black follows the strategy from the
main line:} 10... h5 11. Nxc4 h4 {is this game:} 12. b4 $1 {[#] An excellent
pawn sacrifice. White needs some open files to attack the Black king and one pawn
is the minimal price to pay.} Bxb4 13. Qb3 Nd5 14. Rb1 b6 15. a3 Be7 16. Bd2
hxg3 17. hxg3 f5 18. Rfc1 Kb8 19. Qb5 Qe8 20. a4 $40 {[#] and White's attack
came in faster in Grigoriants, S (2589)-Socko, B (2631) Khanty-Mansiisk RUS 2012}
) 11. Nxc4 (11. Qa4 {is a bit inconsistent now.} exd4 12. exd4 (12. Nxc4 {
-11.Nxc4}) 12... a6 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Qxc6 bxc6 15. Nxc4 Rxd4 16. b3 $44 Re4
17. Bb2 Nd5 18. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Bb4 20. Rc1 f6 21. a3 Be7 22. Na5 c5 23. a4
Rd8 24. Ba3 Nb4 25. Bxb4 cxb4 26. Nc6 Rd7 $11 {1/2 (39) Meier,G (2652)
-Nisipeanu,L (2672) Baden Baden GER 2014}) 11... exd4 {[#] The position has
opened up and White is counting on his bishop pair. He has several good
options at this point:} 12. exd4 (12. Qb3 {The queen and bishop are setting
their sights on the vulnerable b7 pawn and Black's answer is pretty much
forced:} Nd5 13. Bd2 (13. Rd1 Bc5 ({Black took more risks in the following
game:} 13... h5 14. exd4 f6 15. Ne3 Nce7 16. Bd2 h4 17. Rac1 $16 g5 18. a4 $6 (
18. Rc5 $40) 18... hxg3 19. hxg3 Kb8 20. Rc5 c6 21. Rcc1 Nxe3 22. Bxe3 Nd5 23.
Bd2 Bd6 $132 {Schepetkova,M (2244)-Gurvich,V (2305) Voronezh RUS 2018, but
eventually it paid off since White had misplayed her attack.}) 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15.
exd4 {[#] 1-0 (44) Szczepkowska Horowska,K (2406)-Schneider,J (2231) Germany
GER 2018} c6 $146 16. dxc5 Qf5 17. Bxd5 Rxd5 18. Rxd5 cxd5 $11) 13... Bc5 14.
Rac1 dxe3 $1 {[#] Black solves his problems with this move.} 15. Nxe3 Nxe3 16.
Bxe3 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Rhe8 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Rxf7 Qg4 20. Rf4 Qe2 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(24) Sutkalenko,D (2277)-Harabor,M (2290) ICCF email 2017}) (12. Qa4 Nd5 13.
exd4 {[#] This is another important position in the variation with 0-0-0.
Black needs to make sure to keep the blockade on d5.} f6 {is useful for two
reasons: prevents Nc4-e5 and prepares ...g7-g5.} (13... Kb8 14. Rd1 Be7 {
is a different plan - Black wants to attack the d4 pawn instead of the king.}
15. Ne3 $6 ({However, the accurate} 15. Qb3 $1 {exposes Black's problems with
co-ordination of his blockade on d5:} Rhe8 (15... f6 16. Ne3 $16 {[%cal Rc6e7]}
) 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 $36) 15... Nb6 16. Qc2 Bf6 17. d5 Nd4 $132 {1/2-1/2 
(46) Postny,E (2658)-Nakar,E (2463) Skopje MKD 2015}) 14. Rd1 h5 15. a3 (15. h4
g5 $1 16. hxg5 h4 $132) 15... h4 16. Qc2 hxg3 17. hxg3 g5 18. b4 Nce7 $132 {
[#] Black accomplished his strategic goals in this game: d5 is under control,
while h-file is open for counterplay.} 19. Bb2 Kb8 20. Rac1 Bg7 21. Qb3 Rh5 22.
Ne3 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Nd5 $11 24. Qb3 g4 25. b5 f5 26. Rc5 f4 $1 $36 27. Rxd5 Rxd5
28. Qxd5 Qxd5 29. Bxd5 Rxd5 30. gxf4 Rxb5 $17 {1/2-1/2 (71) Khotenashvili,B 
(2426)-Khademalsharieh, S (2435) Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2016}) 12... Qe6 $1 {
[#] This precise move is the key.} (12... Nxd4 $6 13. Be3 Bc5 14. b4 $1 $40 {
gives White an enormous attack.}) 13. Qa4 Rxd4 14. b3 Ne4 $1 {Another precise
move. We get into a forced tactical exchange now:} 15. Bb2 Nc5 16. Qxc6 bxc6
17. Bxd4 Ne4 $1 {[#] White sacrificed his queen for a rook and a minor piece,
but he has ample compensation in the view of his active pieces and Black's
damaged pawn structure. Black's last move is important as he sets up a barrier
on the e-file and the long diagonal, while he completes his development.} 18.
Rae1 ({There are some subtleties involved with development od rooks, as usual:
} 18. Rfe1 f5 19. f3 (19. g4 $6 Qd7 $1 20. Rad1 Bb4 21. Bc3 Qxd1 22. Rxd1 Nxc3
23. Ra1 fxg4 $17 {0-1 (35) Korchmar,V (2450)-Karavade,E (2395) Moscow RUS 2016}
) 19... Qd7 20. Rad1 Bb4 $132 {[#] but Black's idea is the same - remove the
queen from the e-file with a tempo and develop the bishop, also with a tempo!})
18... f5 19. f3 (19. Bxa7 {was seen in a correspondence game:} Kb7 20. Be3 Bb4
21. Rc1 Ra8 {Black coordinated his forces and is doing fine.} 22. Rc2 g5 23.
Rfc1 h5 24. Nd2 Bxd2 25. Bxd2 g4 {1/2-1/2 (25) Fordham Hall,C (2251)-Ivec,I 
