1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8.
e3 Qd7 9. O-O Rd8 $5 {[#] As I explained in the introduction, this fairly new
variation can be a good extra option for Black. If you have studied previous
chapters, it is easy to add 9...Rd8 to your anti-Catalan repertoire. While it
is not nearly as sharp as 9...0-0-0 (the main objective is to equalize rather
than sharpen the game), it could be an extra variation you can use to surprise
your opponents or increase the amount of their pre-game preparation. Black's
main idea is to break in the center with ...e6-e5 and the opening battle
usually revolves around White's attempts to get a favorable type of central
structure with the bishop pair. Let us explore his options, one by one:} 10.
Qe2 {This is the most popular move for White. He simply wants to take the
c4-pawn with the queen.} ({White can also include a developing move} 10. Nc3 {
and Black can respond in kind -} Be7 11. Qe2 (11. Qa4 {is a less accurate
attempt to regain the pawn, due to} Nb4 $1 {[#]} 12. Bxb7 (12. Qxa7 c6 13. a3
Nbd5 14. Qa4 b5 $13) 12... Qxa4 13. Nxa4 Rb8 14. Bg2 Nc2 15. Rb1 Na3 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (19) Ju Wenjun (2580)-Harika, D (2543) Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2016}) 11...
e5 12. Rd1 {White has been successful with this move.} (12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxb7
{is a double-edged approach that worked out for White in this game, but mostly
due to the difference in class. Objectively though, Black is more than fine:}
