Qe7 22. Qf5 Qe6 23. Qa5 $11 {in Xu,X (2585)-Zhou Jianchao (2621) China CHN
2018, left a lot to be desired.}) (12... b5 $6 {was an ambitious, but risky
attempt to keep the extra pawn:} 13. a4 a6 14. axb5 axb5 15. b3 Qd3 16. Qxd3
Nxd3 (16... cxd3 17. Bb2 Bd6 $14) 17. Bc6+ Ke7 18. Nf3 cxb3 19. Rb1 b4 20. Rxb3
Ng4 {1/2-1/2 (30) Cornette,M (2620)-Christiansen,J (2486) Reykjavik ISL 2018}
21. Bb5 Nxc1 22. Rxc1 Kf6 23. Rc6+ Bd6 24. Rxb4 $16) 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 c6
15. b3 (15. e4 $5 {[#] is another plan, which I mentioned in a previous note.
White just wants to play Be3, f4, e5 and dominate in the center. The downside
of this plan is that it weakens d4 square and makes dark squares complex more
vulnerable in general. After} O-O 16. h3 (16. Be3 Ng4 17. Bxa7 b5 18. Qe2 Qxa7
19. Qxg4 Rd2 $132) {I like the following positional idea for Black:} 16... Qd3
$1 ({although the straight-forward} 16... Rfe8 17. Be3 Bf8 18. Rfe1 $14 {
/= should be fine for Black, as well. White will try to utilize his pawn
majority and Black should probably do the same on the other flank.}) 17. Qxd3
Rxd3 18. Be3 Rxe3 $1 {[#] This is the point.} 19. fxe3 Nd7 20. Rad1 Ne5 $44 {
and Black obviously obtains full compensation for the sacrificed exchange.})
15... O-O 16. Bb2 Qf5 {Active and reasonable.} ({Black's play in the following
game was not ideal and he achieved a draw only after a long fight in an
inferior endgame:} 16... a6 17. Rac1 h6 18. e4 Qd3 19. Qxd3 Rxd3 20. e5 Nh7 21.
Be4 Rd2 22. Rc2 Rfd8 23. Bc1 Rxc2 24. Bxc2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (52) Huzman,A (2549)
-Grachev,B (2645) Antalya TUR 2017}) 17. Bd4 (17. e4 Qa5 18. a3 Ng4 19. b4 Qh5
20. h3 Ne5 $132) 17... a6 18. Rac1 Rd7 19. Qc2 {[#] ½-½ (30) Degtiarev,E 
(2402)-Rozentalis,E (2508) Germany GER 2017 and here I would prefer to put the
queen on} Qe6 $5 ({Quite understandably, Black refrains from the queen trade} 
19... Qxc2 20. Rxc2 {since it is very likely that we would get a minor piece
endgame:} Nd5 21. Rd1 Nc7 22. Rcd2 Bb4 23. Rd3 Rfd8 24. Bf1 Nb5 25. Bb2 Rxd3
26. Rxd3 Rxd3 27. Bxd3 Bc3 28. Bc1 $14 {[#] where White's bishop pair gives
him a small, but long-lasting edge.}) 20. Qb2 Rfd8 $14 {/= White still has
some long-terms trumps, but Black is as solid as it gets.}) (10. Qa4 {has been
played in several GM games. After the thematic answer} Nb4 {we get a forced
line:} 11. Qxd7+ Rxd7 12. Na3 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxc4 Nd3 {[#] where Black's
powerful knight on d3 gives him all reasons to be happy with the outcome of
the opening. Examples below look encouraging:} 15. b3 (15. Na5 {½-½ (49)
Turner,M (2523)-Cornette,M (2597) London ENG 2016} Bb6 $1 $146 {[#]} 16. Nxb7 (
16. Nc4 Bc5 $11) 16... Nd5 17. Rd1 Ne5 $1 (17... Nxc1 18. Raxc1 Rxb7 19. Rc8+
Bd8 20. e4 $36) 18. e4 Nb4 19. Rxd7 Kxd7 20. Bf4 Nbd3 $36) 15... O-O ({Keeping
the king in the center} 15... Ke7 $5 {[#] should be even more principled.} 16.
a4 Rhd8 (16... Rc8 17. Bd2 Bb4 18. Bxb4+ Nxb4 19. Rfd1 Rcc7 20. Rdc1 Nd3 $15 {
1/2-1/2 (37) Kozul,Z (2607)-Saduakassova,D (2460) Sitges ESP 2017}) 17. Bd2 Bb4
18. Bxb4+ Nxb4 19. a5 Rc7 20. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Nd7 22. Bf3 Nc5 $15 {1/2-1/2
(51) Batchuluun,T (2568)-Sivuk,V (2560) Sanya City CHN 2017}) 16. Ba3 Bxa3 17.
Nxa3 Rfd8 18. Rfd1 Ng4 19. Rd2 {[#]} Ngxf2 $1 20. Rxf2 Nxf2 21. Kxf2 Rd2+ 22.
Kf3 R8d5 $1 $36 23. g4 b5 $1 24. h3 h5 25. Bf1 a6 $17 {0-1 (48) Bai,J (2537)
-Bu Xiangzhi (2715) Shenzhen CHN 2016}) ({Finally, there is also} 10. Nd2 {
when Black gets to keep his extra pawn with} b5 {White had compensation in the
game below:} 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Qe2 a6 13. Bd2 Nd5 {[#] but went wrong with} 14.
b3 $2 (14. Rfc1 $142 Nb6 15. b3 $44) 14... c3 15. Be1 b4 16. Qxa6 O-O $17 {
0-1 (48) Saduakassova,D (2428)-Ju Wenjun (2579) Doha QAT 2016}) 10... e5 11.
Qxc4 (11. Nc3 {transposes into a line analyzed above.} Be7 {-10.Nc3}) 11...
exd4 {[#]} {Now, White should continue} 12. Qb5 $1 ({since} 12. exd4 Nxd4 {
[#] does not offer him much in return for the central pawn. White has tried
several things in this position:} 13. Nc3 (13. Re1+ Be7 14. Be3 c5 15. b4 $2 (
15. Bxd4 $142 cxd4 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Nf3 d3 18. Rad1 $11) 15... cxb4 16. Bxd4
Qxd4 17. Qxd4 Rxd4 $17 {0-1 (33) Chekletsov,I (2391)-Torma,R (2499) Budapest
HUN 2017}) (13. Bg5 $6 Be7 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Rad1 {0-1 (32) Woellermann,J (2384)
-Basso,P (2460) Douglas 2017} (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 c6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Rad1
b5 19. Qd3 c5 $17 {0-1 (59) Rozum,I (2586)-Grachev,B (2645) Sochi 2017}) 15...
b5 16. Qd3 c5 $15) (13. Bxb7 $2 {is just bad since the bishop can be cut off
with} c6 $1 14. Ba6 Qh3 15. f3 Rd5 $1 16. Re1+ Kd8 $40 {and White is under a
strong attack.}) 13... Be7 14. Bxb7 c6 {[#]} 15. Rd1 (15. Be3 $4 {was a
blunder in a blitz game.} Nf3+ 16. Kg2 Qxb7 17. Kxf3 c5+ 18. Ke2 Qxb2+ $19 {
0-1 (28) Lou Yiping (2484)-Wang Hao (2710) Tianjin CHN 2018}) 15... Qxb7 16.
Rxd4 O-O $11) (12. Rd1 $5 {is also possible, transposing into a line above:}
Be7 13. Nc3 O-O {-10.Nc3}) 12... Rb8 13. Rd1 {[#] After he forced black rook
to b8, White is ready to win the pawn back and play the middlegame with the
"isolani" on d4.} a6 14. Qf1 $5 {A clever manoeuvre that prepares Bg2-h3.} ({
Andreikin's choice was} 14. Qc4 Bd6 15. exd4 O-O 16. Nc3 h6 {[#] but Black had
no problems equalizing after} 17. Nd5 $5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Rfe8 19. Be3 Ne7 20. Qh5
Qf5 21. Qxf5 Nxf5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34) Andreikin,D (2736)-Lu Shanglei (2619)
China CHN 2016}) 14... Bd6 15. exd4 O-O {[#] In this isolated queen's pawn
position, rather than setting up a kingside attack, White hopes to use his
bishop pair and spatial advantage to put positional pressure on Black. The
next move is a part of this plan and a logical follow-up to his 14th move:} 16.
Bh3 Qd8 17. Nc3 ({In the following correspondence game, White used an original
plan to plant his knight on e5.} 17. Qc4 h6 18. a3 Re8 19. b4 Ne7 $1 {[#] This
maneuver is the key - as is well known from IQP theory, the isolated pawn has
to be blocked first, attacked later.} 20. Bb2 Ned5 21. Nd2 Qe7 22. Qf1 c6 23.
Nc4 {The bishop looks poor on b2, but it supports Ne5. This was White's idea.}
Qc7 24. Bg2 Re7 25. Re1 Rbe8 26. Rxe7 Qxe7 27. Ne5 {[#] Despite White's
achievement, Black proved that his position is solid enough:} Qd8 28. Qd3 h5
29. Bf3 Qc8 30. h4 g6 31. Rd1 Qh3 $11 {1/2-1/2 (45) Gleyzer,L (2283)-Baer,L 
(2266) ICCF email 2014}) 17... h6 18. Qc4 Re8 19. Be3 Ne7 {[#] Black prepares
to take d5-square under control.} 20. Re1 ({White could prevent him from doing
that by playing} 20. d5 {but this creates some new outposts for Black pieces.}
Ng6 $13 {and Black knight gets to e5.}) 20... c6 21. Bd2 Qb6 {Black is fine
with the endgame,} ({although he had a reasonable alternative in} 21... Qc7 $5
22. Qb3 Rbd8 23. Rad1 Ng6 $13 {[#] with a complex middlegame. It is important
to remember that} 24. d5 {can always be met with} c5 $132) 22. Na4 Qb5 23. Qxb5
axb5 24. Nc5 {1/2-1/2 (76) Tomashevsky,E (2722)-Bu Xiangzhi (2698) Novi Sad
SRB 2016} {and here after} Red8 25. Re2 Ned5 26. a3 Bc7 $11 {[#] Black would
remain rock-solid.} *

